{"pageContext":{"id":"605814","parent":"__SOURCE__","slug":"chinese-netizens-searched-2018","internal":{"contentDigest":"d95bf6590c09d622c9dbdaab5a6ff26c","type":"ContentCoPost","owner":"default-site-plugin"},"children":[],"title":"What great firewall? Here’s what Chinese netizens searched for in 2018","preview":{"source":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games.jpg","attachment_meta":{"width":720,"height":419,"sizes":{"thumbnail":{"width":100,"height":100,"url":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games-100x100.jpg"},"medium":{"width":350,"height":203,"url":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games-350x203.jpg"},"tia_thumb350_150":{"width":350,"height":150,"url":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games-350x150.jpg"},"tia_thumb60_60":{"width":60,"height":60,"url":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games-60x60.jpg"},"tia_thumb285_285":{"width":285,"height":285,"url":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games-285x285.jpg"},"tia_thumb727_300":{"width":720,"height":300,"url":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games-720x300.jpg"},"tia_thumb174_74":{"width":174,"height":74,"url":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games-174x74.jpg"},"post-thumbnail":{"width":125,"height":125,"url":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games-125x125.jpg"},"ngfb-open-graph":{"width":400,"height":300,"url":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games-400x300.jpg"},"ngfb-opengraph":{"width":350,"height":419,"url":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games-350x419.jpg"}}}},"createdAt":"2018-12-17T05:34:01","content":"<p class=\"article-body-text arrow-placement\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">The “great firewall” segregates China’s cyberspace from the rest of the world. Websites like <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/big-guns/google-app-isnt-banned-china-and-it-has-plenty-users/article/2146686\" data-link-type=\"node\" data-link-subtype=\"article\" data-link-id=\"2146686\" data-link-href=\"/big-guns/google-app-isnt-banned-china-and-it-has-plenty-users/article/2146686\" data-link-title=\"This Google app isn't banned in China -- and it has plenty of users\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Google</a> and <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/digital-life/twitch-vanishes-china-weeks-after-spike-popularity/article/2165056\" data-link-type=\"node\" data-link-subtype=\"article\" data-link-id=\"2165056\" data-link-href=\"/digital-life/twitch-vanishes-china-weeks-after-spike-popularity/article/2165056\" data-link-title=\"Twitch vanishes in China weeks after spike in popularity\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Twitch</a> are blocked in the country, and content deemed inappropriate by authorities is <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/topics/censorship\" data-link-type=\"term\" data-link-subtype=\"topics\" data-link-id=\"326780\" data-link-href=\"/topics/censorship\" data-link-title=\"Censorship\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">heavily censored</a>. But despite the information gap, it turns out that Chinese netizens are curious about many of the same topics and issues as their global counterparts.</p>\n<p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">This week, both Google and China’s top search engine Baidu revealed the past year’s top queries on their respective platforms. The lists provide a glimpse of what matters to people inside China versus those outside.</p>\n<div class=\"related-person-group exclude\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">\n<div class=\"related-person-group-wrapper hidden-sm-down gtm-onElementVisiblity\" data-v-a520eb78=\"\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\" data-ev-category=\"Whatis button\" data-ev-action=\"Whatis widget impression\" data-ev-label=\"/who-what/meet-baidu-chinas-homegrown-search-engine/article/2170204\" data-gtm-vis-first-on-screen-7381696_24=\"299787\">\n<div class=\"related-person-wrapper hidden-sm-down\" data-v-a520eb78=\"\">\n<div class=\"related-person-widget up\" data-v-a520eb78=\"\">\n<div class=\"related-person up\" data-v-a520eb78=\"\">\n<div class=\"related-person-detail up\" data-v-a520eb78=\"\">\n<div class=\"related-person-brief\" data-v-a520eb78=\"\">\n<p>One of China’s three tech titans (it’s the B in BAT), Baidu is effectively the country’s Google. It’s China’s biggest search engine and the world’s fourth most visited website. The company is now investing heavily in AI and self-driving cars.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">\n<h2><strong>Everyone loves the World Cup and the royal wedding</strong></h2>\n</div>\n<figure class=\"img-caption-processed\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\"><div class=\"image\">\n<div class=\"wp-caption alignnone\">\n<img class=\"image-1320w caption\" title=\"World Cup fans watched Russia vs Saudi Arabia at a bar in Beijing in June, 2018. (Picture: Reuters)\" src=\"https://cdn1.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/styles/1320w/public/2018/12/14/world_cup_beijing.jpg?itok=wMZrPLdC\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"683\" data-src=\"https://cdn1.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/styles/1320w/public/2018/12/14/world_cup_beijing.jpg?itok=wMZrPLdC\" data-style-type=\"default\" data-writer=\"Staff\"><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">World Cup fans watch the Russia vs Saudi Arabia match at a bar in Beijing in June 2018. / Photo credit: Reuters</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</figure><p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">The World Cup truly brings the world together. The football tournament was trending across the globe. In China, one streaming platform <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/digital-life/short-video-real-winner-chinas-world-cup-viewers-reach-new-heights/article/2155738\" data-link-type=\"node\" data-link-subtype=\"article\" data-link-id=\"2155738\" data-link-href=\"/digital-life/short-video-real-winner-chinas-world-cup-viewers-reach-new-heights/article/2155738\" data-link-title=\"Short video is the real winner as China’s World Cup viewers reach new heights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">recorded more than 4.3 billion individual views</a> of Russia 2018 matches.</p>\n<p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">Why such enthusiasm from a country that didn’t have a team in the tournament? It might have stemmed partly from its people’s love for gambling. During the World Cup, half of the top 10 free apps on Apple’s App Store in China were lottery apps, <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/digital-life/betting-world-cup-online-just-got-harder-china/article/2151855\" data-link-type=\"node\" data-link-subtype=\"article\" data-link-id=\"2151855\" data-link-href=\"/digital-life/betting-world-cup-online-just-got-harder-china/article/2151855\" data-link-title=\"Betting on the World Cup online just got harder in China\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">leading to an apparent government crackdown</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">China also shared its obsession on Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex, and Meghan Markle with the rest of the world. The royal wedding in May topped both Google and Baidu’s rankings.</p>\n<p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">But it wasn’t just the happy stuff. Disasters were also on people’s minds everywhere: Hurricane Florence, which raged through the US East Coast in September, was the second most searched news on Google. Baidu’s list was topped by <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/big-guns/iphone-xs-track-after-typhoon-mangkhut-barrels-through-chinas-electronics-capital/article/2164532\" data-link-type=\"node\" data-link-subtype=\"article\" data-link-id=\"2164532\" data-link-href=\"/big-guns/iphone-xs-track-after-typhoon-mangkhut-barrels-through-chinas-electronics-capital/article/2164532\" data-link-title=\"iPhone XS on track after Typhoon Mangkhut barrels through China’s electronics capital\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Typhoon Mangkhut</a>, the mega storm that battered China’s tech manufacturing hub in the same month.</p>\n<div class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">\n<h2><strong>China cares about the trade war, Apple, and Facebook</strong></h2>\n</div>\n<figure class=\"img-caption-processed\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\"><div class=\"image\">\n<div class=\"wp-caption alignnone\">\n<img class=\"image-1320w caption\" title=\"Huawei finds a good ad spot: Outside an Apple store in Shanghai in November, 2018. (Picture: Bloomberg)\" src=\"https://cdn1.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/styles/1320w/public/2018/12/14/apple_store_huawei_ad.jpg?itok=Jzs4yWnf\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"683\" data-src=\"https://cdn1.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/styles/1320w/public/2018/12/14/apple_store_huawei_ad.jpg?itok=Jzs4yWnf\" data-style-type=\"default\" data-writer=\"Staff\"><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Huawei finds a good ad spot – outside an Apple store in Shanghai in November 2018. / Photo credit: Bloomberg</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</figure><p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">The trade war between the US and China, as well as <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/digital-life/apples-rivals-china-pounce-new-iphones/article/2164055\" data-link-type=\"node\" data-link-subtype=\"article\" data-link-id=\"2164055\" data-link-href=\"/digital-life/apples-rivals-china-pounce-new-iphones/article/2164055\" data-link-title=\"Apple’s rivals in China pounce on the new iPhones\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Apple’s iPhone launch</a> in September, dominated Baidu searches, but they weren’t among the 10 most googled news events.</p>\n<p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">Even more interesting was another headline that made Baidu’s list, but not Google’s: Facebook’s security breach. The incident, which came to light in September, exposed data from some 50 million accounts.</p>\n<p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">Facebook, of course, is still banned in China despite <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/big-guns/did-facebook-just-get-blocked-opening-company-china/article/2156899\" data-link-type=\"node\" data-link-subtype=\"article\" data-link-id=\"2156899\" data-link-href=\"/big-guns/did-facebook-just-get-blocked-opening-company-china/article/2156899\" data-link-title=\"Did Facebook just get blocked from opening a company in China?\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">continuous attempts</a> by the company’s founder Mark Zuckerberg to woo the country. But the unusual Chinese interest may reflect growing awareness of personal privacy in the country. Ironically, earlier this year, <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/big-guns/chinese-internet-users-criticize-baidu-ceo-saying-people-china-are-willing-give-data-privacy/article/2139313\" data-link-type=\"node\" data-link-subtype=\"article\" data-link-id=\"2139313\" data-link-href=\"/big-guns/chinese-internet-users-criticize-baidu-ceo-saying-people-china-are-willing-give-data-privacy/article/2139313\" data-link-title=\"Chinese internet users criticize Baidu CEO for saying people in China are willing to give up data privacy for convenience\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Baidu CEO and co-founder Robin Li</a> (or Li Yanhong) came under fire for saying the people in China are willing to give up data privacy for convenience.</p>\n<div class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">\n<h2><strong>Backstabbing concubines conquered the world</strong></h2>\n</div>\n<figure class=\"img-caption-processed\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\"><div class=\"image\">\n<div class=\"wp-caption alignnone\">\n<img class=\"image-1320w caption\" title=\"The Story of Yanxi Palace was a 70-episode epic. Disclaimer: I watched all of them. (Picture: iQiyi)\" src=\"https://cdn1.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/styles/1320w/public/2018/12/14/yanxi_couple.jpg?itok=pq6w2AS9\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"683\" data-src=\"https://cdn1.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/styles/1320w/public/2018/12/14/yanxi_couple.jpg?itok=pq6w2AS9\" data-style-type=\"default\" data-writer=\"Staff\"><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">The Story of Yanxi Palace was a 70-episode epic. (Disclosure: I watched all of them.) / Photo credit: iQiyi</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</figure><p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">It’s not exactly a surprise to find the Chinese TV blockbuster <em>The Story of Yanxi Palace</em> on Baidu’s list. But it’s worth noting that the historical drama about scheming imperial concubines was also this year’s most googled TV show, beating Netflix’s <em>Altered Carbon</em> and the controversial ABC sitcom <em>Roseanne</em>.</p>\n<p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">In China, <em>The Story of Yanxi Palace</em> aired exclusively on Baidu’s streaming platform iQiyi, drawing 300 million daily views during its run. It was also shown around the world, including on one Vietnamese site that <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/digital-life/website-forces-viewers-take-political-quiz-watching-hit-chinese-tv-show/article/2160990\" data-link-type=\"node\" data-link-subtype=\"article\" data-link-id=\"2160990\" data-link-href=\"/digital-life/website-forces-viewers-take-political-quiz-watching-hit-chinese-tv-show/article/2160990\" data-link-title=\"Website forces viewers to take political quiz before watching hit Chinese TV show \" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">forced viewers to answer a politically sensitive quiz</a> to see it, stoking a wave of patriotic wrath on Chinese social media.</p>\n<div class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">\n<h2><strong>RIP Stan Lee and Stephen Hawking</strong></h2>\n</div>\n<figure class=\"img-caption-processed\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\"><div class=\"image\">\n<div class=\"wp-caption alignnone\">\n<img class=\"image-1320w caption\" title=\"Stephen Hawking at an event in Cambridge, England in 2016 (left) and Stan Lee at the TCL Chinese Theater in Hollywood in 2017. (Pictures: AFP Photo/EPA-EFE)\" src=\"https://cdn1.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/styles/1320w/public/2018/12/14/stan_lee_hawking.jpeg?itok=jbDHkTt0\" alt=\"\" width=\"1320\" height=\"768\" data-src=\"https://cdn1.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/styles/1320w/public/2018/12/14/stan_lee_hawking.jpeg?itok=jbDHkTt0\" data-style-type=\"default\" data-writer=\"Staff\"><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Stephen Hawking at an event in Cambridge, England in 2016 (left) and Stan Lee at the TCL Chinese Theater in Hollywood in 2017 / Photo credits: AFP Photo and EPA-EFE</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</figure><p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">Netizens on both sides of the great firewall mourned the passing of Marvel Comics legend Stan Lee and renowned physicist Stephen Hawking. The two men had a massive following in China. Hawking blogged on Weibo where he answered public questions, while Lee’s superheroes were part of several movies that became box office hits in China.</p>\n<p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">Weibo is a Twitter-like microblogging service used by hundreds of millions of users. Launched by Sina in 2009, it regularly censors topics deemed sensitive or inappropriate by the Chinese government.</p>\n<div class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">\n<h2><strong>Skr</strong></h2>\n</div>\n<figure class=\"img-caption-processed\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\"><div class=\"image\">\n<div class=\"wp-caption alignnone\">\n<img class=\"image-1320w caption\" title=\"Kris Wu featured in a Xiaomi smartphone ad in Hong Kong. (Picture: SCMP)\" src=\"https://cdn1.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/styles/1320w/public/2018/12/14/kris_wu_xiaomi.jpg?itok=tLEkGecm\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"589\" data-src=\"https://cdn1.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/styles/1320w/public/2018/12/14/kris_wu_xiaomi.jpg?itok=tLEkGecm\" data-style-type=\"default\" data-writer=\"Staff\"><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Chinese-Canadian celebrity Kris Wu on a Xiaomi ad in Hong Kong / Photo credit: SCMP</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</figure><p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">It certainly wasn’t on Google’s list, but “skr” was China’s buzzword of the year according to Baidu.</p>\n<p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">It’s hard to lock down what it exactly means. The term was popularized by Kris Wu, the Chinese-Canadian rapper who was accused last month of <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/digital-life/chinese-rapper-topped-ariana-grande-itunes-sales-did-bots-buy-his-songs/article/2172044\" data-link-type=\"node\" data-link-subtype=\"article\" data-link-id=\"2172044\" data-link-href=\"/digital-life/chinese-rapper-topped-ariana-grande-itunes-sales-did-bots-buy-his-songs/article/2172044\" data-link-title=\"A Chinese rapper topped Ariana Grande in iTunes sales. But did bots buy his songs?\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">using bots to jack up iTunes sales</a> to beat Ariana Grande. On last year’s hit reality TV show <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/future-tech/ai-successfully-predicts-show-will-be-hit-it-airs/article/2131427\" data-link-type=\"node\" data-link-subtype=\"article\" data-link-id=\"2131427\" data-link-href=\"/future-tech/ai-successfully-predicts-show-will-be-hit-it-airs/article/2131427\" data-link-title=\"AI successfully predicts show will be a hit before it airs\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>The Rap of China</em></a>, Wu used the catchphrase to praise the contestants he liked.</p>\n<p class=\"article-body-text\" data-v-46c6605a=\"\">But not everyone agrees. <a href=\"https://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=skr%20skr\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">One popular entry</a> on Urban Dictionary defined skr as a term “misused by Canadian so-called rapper Kris Wu.” Others think it’s just a verbal equivalent to <a href=\"https://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=facepalm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">facepalm</a>.</p>\n<div>\n<p><em>For <span class=\"il\">more</span> on China tech, visit <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/?utm_source=TIA&amp;utm_medium=partner&amp;utm_campaign=contentexchangeabacus\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-saferedirecturl=\"https://www.google.com/url?q=https://www.abacusnews.com/?utm_source%3DTIA%26utm_medium%3Dpartner%26utm_campaign%3Dcontentexchangeabacus&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1544070450615000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGbIWMSvlKsQ5PgS4VKXGhL6TYC_A\">abacusnews.com</a> or subscribe to the newsletter via <a href=\"https://www.abacusnews.com/?utm_source=TIA&amp;utm_medium=partner&amp;utm_campaign=contentexchangeabacus\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-saferedirecturl=\"https://www.google.com/url?q=https://www.abacusnews.com/?utm_source%3DTIA%26utm_medium%3Dpartner%26utm_campaign%3Dcontentexchangeabacus&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1544070450615000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGbIWMSvlKsQ5PgS4VKXGhL6TYC_A\">abacusnews.com/newsletter</a> for the latest China tech news, reviews and product launches.</em></p>\n</div>\n<div><em>Copyright (c) 2018. South China Morning Post Publishers Ltd. All rights reserved.</em></div>","categories":[{"id":"39658","name":"News","slug":"news"}],"author":{"name":"Karen Chiu","image":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/authors/233603.jpg?v=1542096339"},"seo":{"title":"What Chinese netizens searched for in 2018","description":"The World Cup, the Royal Wedding, and concubines topped searches on both Baidu and Google.","image":"https://cdn.techinasia.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chinajoy-baidu-mobile-games.jpg"}}}